05045nam a22005895i 9780773588073DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735880737 a10.1515/97807735880732doi  a(DE-B1597)656382  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPS325b.T56 2013 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a811.54091 aSmith, J. Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTime in Time :bShort Poems, Long Poems, and the Rhetoric of North American Avant-Gardism, 1963-2008 /cJ. Mark Smith. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b5 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Poetic Form and the Rhetoric of North American Avant-Gardism, 1963–2008 -- tLyric and Experimental Long Poems: Intersections -- tMore Apparent than Real: The Lyric/Avant-Garde Divide -- tHannah Weiner’s Book in Air: Clairvoyant Journal and the Clair-Style Poems -- tThe Lyric Turn: A Poetics of Falling -- tBy the Numbers: Jackson Mac Low’s Light Poems and Algorithmic Digraphism -- tBetter Living through ‘Pataphysics: The Biosemiotics of Kenneth Goldsmith -- tGetting Every Word In: A.R. Ammons’s Garbage and the Corpora -- tDay Labour -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEdgar Allan Poe, arguing that brevity and intensity were the essence of poetry, declared there was no such thing as a long poem. It can also be said there is no difference between a short and a long poem except duration: a measure of time. Time in Time examines what the difference really is, and investigates the interplay of short and long forms in contemporary poetry. Moving beyond the opposition of lyric and experimental schools, Time in Time constructs a history of recent North American efforts to bring about a more open poetic form. Contributors explore ways in which the work of Louis Zukofsky, William Carlos Williams, Jackson Mac Low, George Oppen, Hannah Weiner, A.R. Ammons, Marjorie Perloff, Erín Moure, Ron Silliman, and Kenneth Goldsmith reconceives, reframes, and sometimes interknits the possibilities of short and long poems. In doing so, the collection offers insight into the affiliative networks and inter-generational lines of avant-gardism on the continent. Attuned to the surprising reversals and unstable categories of the period, Time in Time illuminates the ongoing encounter of literary creativity with the limits and possibilities of form. Contributors include Adam Dickinson (Brock University), Kerry Doyle (York University), Rachel Blau DuPlessis (Temple University), Steve McCaffery (SUNY Buffalo), Erín Moure (Montreal), Michael O'Driscoll (University of Alberta) Jennifer Russo (City University of New York Graduate Center), and J. Mark Smith (Grant MacEwan University).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aExperimental poetry, Americany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental poetry, Americany21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental poetry, Canadiany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental poetry, Canadiany21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aDickinson, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuPlessis, Rachel Blau, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCaffery, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoure, Erín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato